It is planned to renovate several interior parts of the palace, including two auditoriums, and to make the building accessible for persons with reduced mobility.
The Riga City Council intends to attract EU funding for the project in the amount of six million euros, but Olegs Burovs, the director or the Riga City Council's Property Department, admits that currently there is no absolute clarity about the European money for this project.
"Notwithstanding that, there is a political will to start the repair works at the VEF Culture Palace and attracting European structural funds, we have been waiting for months for a decision, some real move by the officials of the Ministry of Finance, to understand if that money is granted or not," Burovs says.
Last December we were told that it completely depends on Brussels.
Two weeks ago the Ministry of Finance received a letter from the European Commission telling us to make a decision and that Brussels is not the entity to do that.
Now we see that another discussion round is being created, so let's see what to expect in the closest days to come.
"I want to confirm that the Riga City Council definitely guarantees that this process will be begun and completed in a timely manner," Burovs says.
As reported more than a year ago, in March 2015 the arts collectives of the VEF Culture Palace organized a farewell concert since the building's renovation was about to start very soon.
Even though a year has passed, the renovation has not started and the collectives have continued working in unsuitable conditions.
The strategy elaborated by the Riga City Council's Property Department for the renovation of the VEF Culture Palace is divided into seemingly independent units of reconstruction works each of those relate to different functions of the palace.
The first one concerns improvements of the VEF Culture Palace's accessibility and landscaping of the surrounding area.
It implies rebuilding the surrounding territory and utilities as well as renovating the building's exterior.
The second part concerns improvement of the VEF Culture Palace's range of services.
It mentions an improvement of building's interior; wall and ceiling restoration; stage and recording studio improvements; renovating the cabling and plumbing.
The third part: improvement of work conditions of the amateur arts collectives, namely, improvement of workshop equipment, heating and ventilation systems.
Legendary rock band "Livi" 40th anniversary anticipated with exhibition.
The exhibition will feature various items characterizing "Livi": a timeline with photos reflects the band's activities from its beginnings until 2010 when the band officially announced the end of its career.
Band members' costumes, instruments, awards and taped live performances as well as other items yet unseen by a wider public yet telling the story of "Livi" will also be on display.
The exhibition has received some items from the Liepaja Museum collection.
The visual design of the exhibition was created in cooperation with the fashion artist and painter Elita Patmalniece.
Also other musicians who had this or another kind of connection with "Livi" as well as their families came up and shared both items and memories.
The story of "Livi" began in 1972 when Juris Pavitols founded a band of popular music.
The band's first line-up participated in the "Liepajas dzintars" festival in 1972 and 1974 as well as performance review concerts around Latvia.
Year 1976 marked a decisive turn when Juris Pavitols met Eriks Kigelis: the band found a base at the Metal Worker's Culture Hall and invited Ingrida Gutmane, Andris Kruzins and Janis Grodums to join.
Later the band's line-up changed many times.
Some musicians joined, others left and some returned again.
The major, perhaps most enduring motif was the desire to show that the Latvian rock music can live on.
"There was a lot to see: jeans, long hair and beards; these guys were different from the conventional stereotype of a crooner on stage," music journalist Klass Vavere comments about the band.
Such popular musicians as Igo, Vilnis Krievins, Modris Sterns, Valdis Starks, Laims Racenajs, Talis Pusbarnieks, Ainars Virga, Aivars Brize, Guntars Mucenieks, Dainis Virga, Tomass Kleins and many more can be mentioned among the participants of the band.
Entrance to the exhibition is free of charge.
It runs from August 19 until October 30.
On August 27, the 40th anniversary of "Livi" will be marked with "LIVIfest 2" at the Liepaja concert garden "Put, vejini".
Bulgaria Posts Inflation for 1st Time in 8 Months
Inflation in Bulgaria was 1% on a monthly basis in July, national statistics show.
This is the highest value in years (since June 2012) and the first one above zero since October of last year when a positive 0.2% was posted.
The annual average inflation, measured by CPI, in the last 12 months (August 2015 - July 2016) compared to the previous 12 months (August 2014 - July 2015) was -0.8%.
The consumer price index in July 2016 compared to June 2016 was 101.0%, i.e. the monthly inflation was 1.0%.
The inflation rate since the beginning of the year (July 2016 compared to December 2015) has been -0.2% and the annual inflation in July 2016 compared to July 2015 was -0.2%.
In July 2016, compared to the previous month, an increase was observed in the price of the following groups of consumer goods: food and non-alcoholic beverages (1.7%); transport (1.8%); recreation and culture (6.3%); restaurants and hotels (1.2%); miscellaneous goods and services (0.3%).
Prices decreased in clothing and footwear (2.2%); furnishings, household equipment and routine maintenance (0.5%); health (0.1%).
Prices remained at the same level as in the previous month in alcoholic beverages and tobacco; housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels; communications; and education.
